onException(MongoException.class).routeId(ApplicationConstants.ROUTE_ID_MONGOEXECEPTION).handled(true)
                .maximumRedeliveries(numOfRetries).maximumRedeliveryDelay(retryDelay).logRetryAttempted(true)
                .setProperty(LoggingRoutePolicy.PROP_LOG_LEVEL, constant(Level.ERROR))
                .setProperty(error, constant(error))
                .setProperty(httpcode, constant(HttpMessages.HTTP_500))
                .to(ConstantsRest.exceptionBuilder)
                .bean(ResponseBuilder.class, "populateErrorResponse").marshal().json(JsonLibrary.Jackson)
                .setHeader(Exchange.HTTP_RESPONSE_CODE, constant(HttpURLConnection.HTTP_INTERNAL_ERROR))
                .setHeader(Exchange.HTTP_CHUNKED, constant(ApplicationConstants.FALSE))
                .setHeader(Exchange.CONTENT_TYPE, constant(MediaType.APPLICATION_JSON)).end();

 The Retry Strategy (Resilience)
The most important part of this code is the Redelivery Policy:
maximumRedeliveries(numOfRetries): If a MongoException occurs (e.g., a socket timeout or a temporary primary election in your Mongo cluster), Camel will not immediately return an error. It will retry the operation $X$ times.
maximumRedeliveryDelay(retryDelay): This adds a "wait period" between retries. In a distributed system, retrying instantly often leads to more failures. This delay gives the database a few milliseconds/seconds to breathe.
handled(true): This "swallows" the exception. Once the retries are exhausted, Camel stops trying to throw the error further up the chain and instead moves to your custom error-building logic.

